commits.message:
[FIX] account: exchange with same foreign currency not in partial

After https://github.com/odoo/odoo/pull/204746, in some situations we will
default the amount of the partial on residual of debit aml even if this one is
larger than the credit aml amount.
This lead to multiple exchange moves creation that are not properly linked to
the reconciliation chain.

Steps to reproduce:
1/ Setup foreign currency with rate 0.648587 (ex 0.648587 USD = 1 AUD for AUD
company)
2/ Create invoice with lines
36 USD (55.51 AUD)
-7.2 USD (-11.1 AUD)
=> Receivable will be 28.8 USD (44.41 AUD)
3/ Register a payment of 28.8 USD (44.4 AUD)
=> Two exchange moves will be created with 0.01 in credit, none of them is in a
partial with the invoice or payment line

This PR makes sure that we take the smallest amount of residual if both credit
and debit are considered as fully matched.

X-original-commit: a456d9c7cbdf17edb5db2c73306b62150e46a7a7
Signed-off-by: Laurent Smet (las) <las@odoo.com>

[IMP] dun_and_bradstreet: send `industry_code` instead of `industry_id`

Ticket #4992568 highlighted a weird way of sending the industry from
IAP to the Odoo client. Before this commit, we were sending the IAP psql id
of the industry to the client. There, it would be use as is. It works because
these industries haven't been changed in years and they're created in the same
order.
However the ticket highlighted the fact that a user can edit/delete/create its
own industries, therefore some ids that exist on IAP might not exist on the client's
Odoo instance. This resulted in a traceback on the client's side

With this commit, we now send the industry code (the ISIC: International Standard
Industrial Classification) instead to the client. There it can correctly be mapped
if it exists on the client's DB (e.g. not deleted)

X-original-commit: 84fddd21a2b668475f02412792c47df9c75088d4
Signed-off-by: Ricardo Gomes Rodrigues (rigr) <rigr@odoo.com>

[FIX] bus: race condition and correct error in waitForChannels

This change addresses two issues in the `waitForChannels` test utility:
- Fixes a race condition. The `failTimeout` variable was sometimes accessed
before its `setTimeout` declaration had been executed. This happens when a fast
bus event triggers the `onWebsocketEvent` handler, resulting in a reference
error. The variable is now declared at the beginning of the function, making it
available before any access (fixes runbot-223252).
- Corrects error in def.reject. `message` only takes one param, and a string
does not have a join method.

[FIX] point_of_sale: Fixed singleton error

Previously, when duplicating more than one pos.config record,
it would give a singleton error.

This commit adds a for loop to resolve the singleton error.

Steps to reproduce the issue:
1) In the Point of Sale app, when trying to duplicate more than

[FIX] calendar: show meetings with no organizer in grouped view

__Issue__
In the calendar list view, meetings with no organizer and default
privacy (`privacy=False`) are excluded when grouping by Responsible and
Created On.

__Steps to Reproduce__
1. Create a meeting with:
   - `privacy` set to default,
   - no `organizer`
2. Go to Calendar > List view.
3. Group by Responsible, then by Created On.

 The meeting is missing from the view.

__Fix__
Adjust the domain to include meetings where:
- `privacy=False`, and
- either `user_id` is unset or their settings are in the public allowed
list.

pull_request.title: Add filtering options for hoerbuecher episodes table
pull_request.body:
This pull request adds advanced filtering capabilities to the audiobook episodes list, improves the `AudiobookEpisode` model with new accessors for episode type, roles filled, and release year, and refactors date parsing logic for better maintainability. It also introduces tests to ensure correct behavior of the new model accessors.

### Filtering and UI improvements

* Added filter controls to `hoerbuecher/index.blade.php` for status, type, year, and roles filled, allowing users to narrow down episodes in the UI.
* Implemented client-side filtering logic in `hoerbuecher.js` to show/hide episode rows based on selected filter criteria.
* Updated episode table rows to include new data attributes (`data-status`, `data-type`, `data-roles-filled`, `data-year`) for use by the filter logic.

### Model enhancements

* Added new accessors and methods to `AudiobookEpisode.php`: `all_roles_filled`, `isSpecialEdition`, `episode_type`, `planned_release_date_parsed`, and `release_year`, centralizing logic for episode classification and release date parsing.
* Refactored date parsing from controller to model, simplifying the controller and improving code reuse.

### Testing

* Added a feature test suite `AudiobookEpisodeModelTest.php` to verify the new model accessors for episode type, roles filled, and release year.

pull_request.title: fix(core): Heal data conflicts causing Core Lightning payment status errors
pull_request.body:
This PR resolves a cascade of issues originating from legacy data inconsistencies in the apipayments table. The fix implements a self-healing mechanism that automatically cleans up corrupted data over time, resolving stuck pending payments, database crashes, and Core Lightning log spam without requiring any manual user intervention.
The Bug

A legacy bug in the payment creation logic could create two distinct records for a single transaction:

    A "buggy" record where checking_id was an internal database UUID.

    A "correct" record where checking_id was the proper payment hash.

This data corruption led to a chain of failures:

    Stuck Payments & CLN Errors: When a status check was performed on a "buggy" record, its UUID was sent to the Core Lightning node, which correctly rejected it with an Invalid parameter payment_hash error. This caused the payment to be stuck as "pending" indefinitely in the UI and spammed the node's logs.

    Database IntegrityError: Initial attempts to fix this by simply updating the buggy record's checking_id would fail with a UniqueViolationError. The database correctly prevented the update because it would make the buggy record an exact duplicate of the "correct" record that already existed. This crash would halt the background payment checker task.

    Database UndefinedColumnError: An attempt to delete the duplicate buggy record failed due to a simple typo (wallet instead of wallet_id) in the DELETE statement's WHERE clause.

The Fix

This fix is implemented across two commits that work together to create a robust, self-healing system:

    Self-Healing Logic (services/payments.py):
    The core of the solution is in the update_pending_payment function. It now acts as a "heal-on-read" mechanism. When it encounters a potentially buggy record (where checking_id != payment_hash):

        It first queries for a "correct" duplicate record.

        If a correct duplicate exists, the buggy record is safely deleted.

        If no duplicate exists, the buggy record is repaired in-memory before its status is checked.

        This entire process is wrapped in a try/except block to ensure that an error processing one payment does not crash the entire background task.

    CRUD Typo Correction (crud/payments.py):
    The final blocker was a typo in the delete_wallet_payment and get_wallet_payment functions. The SQL query was incorrectly referencing a column named wallet instead of the correct wallet_id. This commit corrects the typo, allowing the self-healing logic in the service layer to function as intended.

AI Assistance and Production Validation

It is important to note that this complex issue was debugged and resolved in close collaboration with a generative AI assistant (Google's Gemini). The AI played a significant role in analyzing the chain of error logs across multiple system layers, tracing the logic through the LNbits codebase, and iteratively refining the final self-healing solution.

Furthermore, this exact code is currently running in a production environment for the [Lightning Goats](https://www.google.com/url?sa=E&q=https%3A%2F%2Flightninggoats.com) project. Since deployment, it has been confirmed to resolve all three classes of errors: the Core Lightning Invalid parameter logs have ceased, the database IntegrityError and UndefinedColumnError crashes have been eliminated, and stuck pending payments are being correctly updated.

issue.title: feat: Add Smart Progress Dashboard with GitHub-Style Streak Calendar
issue.body:
I have added a fully-featured Smart Progress Dashboard designed to enhance user engagement through real-time analytics, gamified tracking, and a GitHub-style contribution calendar.

** Key Features**
- **GitHub-Style Streak Calendar**: Visual contribution heatmap with 53-week year view and activity levels
- **Real-time Progress Tracking**: Automatic challenge completion tracking with local Storage persistence
- **Interactive Analytics**: Radar charts for skills, bar charts for activity patterns
- **Achievement System**: Unlockable badges with progress milestones
- **Goal Setting Interface**: Create and track coding objectives with progress indicators

** Technical Implementation**
- **GitHub Calendar Integration**: Authentic contribution-style visualization with hover tooltips
- **Chart.js Integration**: Professional interactive charts for skill breakdown
- **Local Storage Persistence**: Privacy-focused data storage with demo data support
- **Event-based Tracking**: Seamless integration with existing "Solve Challenge" buttons
- **Responsive Design**: Mobile-optimized calendar and dashboard components

** Dashboard Components Added**
- `scripts/progress-dashboard.js` - Main dashboard analytics engine
- `scripts/demo-data.js` - Sample data initialization for dashboard preview
- `scripts/streak-goal-manager.js` - GitHub-style calendar and goal management
- `styles/progress-dashboard.css` - Professional dashboard styling
- `styles/streak-calendar.css` - GitHub contribution calendar styling
- `styles/goal-setting.css` - Goal setting interface styling
-  `PROGRESS_DASHBOARD_README.md` - The Total documentation of the SMART ANALYSIS DASHBOARD

 ** Smart Analytics Features**
- **Skill Radar**: Visual breakdown of coding abilities across categories
- **Streak Tracking**: Current streak, longest streak, and total contributions
- **Achievement Gallery**: Unlockable badges for various coding milestones
- **Personal Insights**: Data-driven recommendations and progress encouragement
- **Activity Heatmap**: GitHub-style daily coding activity visualization

** Dashboard Benefits**
- **User Engagement**: Gamified progress tracking increases motivation
- **Visual Progress**: Clear insights into coding journey and skill development
- **Goal Achievement**: Set and track personalized coding objectives
- **Streak Motivation**: GitHub-style calendar encourages daily coding habits
- **Performance Analytics**: Comprehensive view of learning patterns

Ready to enhance user engagement with smart analytics! 
The final Change Output :

comment.body:
##  CodeRabbitAI Review Feedback Addressed

Fixed in commit [96adf6d](https://github.com/sasazame/personal-hub-cf/commit/96adf6d).

### Changes implemented:

**Pagination hardening:**
-  Added robust parsing with `Number.parseInt(..., 10)` and explicit fallbacks
-  Normalize NaN/negative page values to 0
-  Normalize NaN/zero/negative size values to default 20
-  Cap size to MAX_SIZE of 100 to prevent excessive queries
-  Fixed totalPages calculation to handle division by zero
-  Added comprehensive test coverage for all edge cases

**Type safety improvements:**
-  Added enum validation for `sessionType` in `createSessionSchema`
-  Updated frontend to use `SessionType` enum instead of strings
-  Fixed `prepareSessionData` to dynamically set `breakDuration` based on session type

**Task creation fix:**
-  Fixed orderIndex derivation from array index instead of expecting it from frontend

**Performance optimizations:**
-  Removed unnecessary 500ms setTimeout delays in auto-start logic

All tests passing, type-checking clean, and builds successful. Thank you for the thorough review\!

issue.title: v6.3.6 Unstable Behavior
issue.body:
I tested firmware v6.3.6 and found that it behaves very unstably. 
After turning the power on and off several times, the LCD stops displaying anything. 
Once this state occurs, the device cannot be recovered without rewriting the firmware.

When I reverted to v6.3.4, the issue did not occur. 
However, the same issue occurred again after flashing v6.3.6.

Note: I have not tested v6.3.5.
